definition.value: Catalysis of the cyclization of (S)-2,3-epoxysqualene to form a triterpene.
Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the neck of a fungal bud before and during cytokinesis.
Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the tip of a growing fungal bud.
Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the tip of a growing fungal hypha.
Protein complex that has a role in determining cell polarity, found at the tip of the mating projection in unicellular fungi exposed to mating pheromone.
Regulation of transcription by a mechanism that allows RNA polymerase to continue transcription beyond a termination site.
A protein complex that possesses AMP-dependent protein kinase activity.

The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of wybutosine, 3H-imidazo[1,2-alpha]purine-7-butanoic acid, 4,9-dihydro- alpha-[(methoxycarbonyl)amino]- 4,6-dimethyl-9-oxo- 3-beta-D-ribofuranosyl methyl ester, a modified nucleoside found in some tRNA molecules.
An amorphous structure surrounding the core of the centrosome, from which microtubules are nucleated -  contains gamma-tubulin.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a polymer of ubiqutin.

The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a change in post-synaptic potential.
A proteasome found in the nucleus of a cell.
A proteasome found in the endoplasmic reticulum of a cell.
A proteasome complex found in the cytosol of a cell.
The regulatory subcomplex of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.
The regulatory subcomplex of a proteasome located in the endoplasmic reticulum of a cell.

A multisubunit complex located in the cytosol of a cell, which caps one or both ends of the proteasome core complex. This complex recognizes, unfolds ubiquitinated proteins and translocates them to the proteasome core complex.
The core complex of a proteasome located in the nucleus of a cell.
The core complex of a proteasome located in the endoplasmic reticulum of a cell.
The core complex of a proteasome located in the cytosol of a cell.

A centrosome from which one pole of a mitotic or meiotic spindle is organized.
A supercomplex formed by the association of two subcomplexes (known as MIND and Ndc80 in Schizosaccharomyces) with additional proteins at the kinetochores of condensed nuclear chromosomes.
Nuclear heterochromatin that is located adjacent to the CENP-A rich centromere 'central core' and characterized by the modified histone H3K9me3.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a ubiquitin conjugating enzyme, any of the E2 proteins.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an opioid receptor.

Any process that affects the structure and integrity of a protein by altering the likelihood of its degradation or aggregation.
Any process that decreases the stability of a protein, making it more vulnerable to degradative processes or aggregation.
The dark-staining region of a sarcomere, in which myosin thick filaments are present -  the center is traversed by the paler H zone, which in turn contains the M line.

A relatively pale zone traversing the center of the A band of a sarcomere, visible in relaxed muscle fibers -  consists of the central portion of thick (myosin) filaments that are not overlapped by thin (actin) filaments.

A region of a sarcomere that appears as a light band on each side of the Z disc, comprising a region of the sarcomere where thin (actin) filaments are not overlapped by thick (myosin) filaments -  contains actin, troponin, and tropomyosin -  each sarcomere includes half of an I band at each end.
The pigmented membrane of a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NADH + H+ + plastoquinone -eq- NAD+ + plastoquinol.
The heterodimer formed by the beta and gamma subunits of a heterotrimeric G protein, which dissociates from the alpha subunit upon guanine nuclotide exchange.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a G-protein beta subunit.
